<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776695>
        a                        fabio:Figure ;
        dc:description           "FIGURE 5. Tolypothrix pseudorexia Novis & Visnovsky (photographed from culture LCR-CYTR). A–L light micrographs, M–N transmission electron micrographs. A. Profile of colony on agar, showing erect trichomes (arrow). B. Typical false branch arising from a heterocyte (arrow) with single pore. C. Adjacent false branches (arrows) giving the superficial appearance of scytonematoid structure. D. False branches are often seen to form right angles; these may be the result of hormogone adhesion rather than trichome division. E. On 10% BG-11 medium the heterocytes (h) are often reduced, but still evident at the branch points. F. Adjacent intercalary heterocytes preceding trichome division (arrow). G. Development is isopolar in young hormogonia. H. A heterocyte develops at one end (arrow) and this end widens. I. Growth continues from the other end of the hormogonium (arrow). J. The heterocytous end of the hormogone possesses a mucilage pad (arrow). K. This pad frequently adheres to another trichome. L. Growth from the adhered trichomes leads to a network of branches, potentially explaining the profile of the colony in A. M. Cells in longitudinal section showing layered sheath (s) and lighter central area (ca). N. Cell in transverse section showing peripheral infolded thylakoid membranes (tm), which are not widened. Scales: 0.5 mm in A, 50 µm in E (use for B–L), 1 µm in M (use for M–N)." ;
        fabio:hasRepresentation  "https://zenodo.org/record/4776695/files/figure.png" .

